    -ms-user-select: none;
    user-select: none;
}

To address the concerns of those who find the show to be too long and boring (thanks largely to the current existence of 24 competitive awards, of which the general public only cares about a few), Bailey and Academy CEO Dawn Hudson said in a letter to members that the board has \"committed to producing an entertaining show in three hours.\" They explain that this will be achieved partly by \"present[ing] select categories live, in the Dolby Theatre, during commercial breaks (categories to be determined).\" Those categories will not be removed from the telecast; instead, \"the winning moments will then be edited and aired later in the broadcast.\" This new format is similar to the one employed at the Tony Awards, which are annually broadcast on CBS, to recognize some of its lower-profile categories. (The Tonys present those awards and record acceptance speeches of them during a pretelecast portion of the ceremony, rather than during commercial breaks. Presenting them during commercial breaks is probably intended to make nominees in those categories feel more integrated into the heart of the telecast.) The fact that this change has been endorsed by the Academy's board of governors, which is dominated by representatives of \"below-the-line\" branches whose Oscar winners could be impacted by this, is a testament to how dire the situation is, as far as the telecast's ratings. of 2021, will see NASA design and build the experimental aircraft. The plane aims to cruise at around 16500 metres and travel at speeds of about 1500 km\/h. \n\nIts stand-out feature is the quiet supersonic technology that aerospace company Lockheed Martin has been contracted to develop, meaning the plane would emit minimal noise, rather than the sonic boom typical of other supersonic planes. \n\nCurrent regulations ban commercial supersonic aircraft from operating over land but the space company's new technology could support a review of this law, potentially opening up new commercial cargo and passenger markets using faster-than-sound air travel. \n\nIt is expected the plane will create a sound about as loud as a car door closing, rendering it almost inaudible to those on the ground. This important step will also be tested over selected US cities. \n\nThe data collected from surveys with residents will be sent to US and international regulators for use in \"considering new Torpedoed around 300 miles off the coast of Ireland, the ship then sank almost 4,700 metres to the bottom of the North Atlantic Ocean. It lay there forgotten for 70 years. Fast forward to 2011, marine archaeologists discovered the long-lost shipwreck. \n\nIn its cargo sat millions of ounces of silver, sent from colonial India to the UK to help fund the war effort. But as divers sifted through the wreckage, another surprising discovery appeared. \n\n\"And in the conservation lab, slowly and suddenly words and phrases started to appear. And now this turned out to be a collection of some 700 letters, written from British India in November and December 1940. It's the largest collection of letters to survive on any shipwreck, anywhere in the world, since people started to write,\" said Marine Archaeologist and Guest Curator Dr. Sean Kingsley. \n\n\"It shouldn't have been preserved, but because there was no light, there was no oxygen, it was darkness, it was like putting a collection of organics in a tin can, sealing it up and putting it in a fridge freezer,\" explained Dr. Kingsley. \n\nWritten 77 years ago and never delivered, the letters shed light on correspondence during the war. There are examples of soldiers writing to loved ones, businessmen and missionaries. \n\nOne joyful letter, written on 1 December 1940 by Private Pete Walker is to his \"most precious sweetheart\" Phyll. \n\nWalker writes how he'd \"wept with joy\" after she accepted his marriage proposal, her acceptance was also sent via mail. \n\n\"He has received her acceptance of his offer of marriage, all conducted through the post,\" explains Emma Harper, exhibitions officer at The Postal Museum. \n\n\"And it's just so gushing, he says; 'I wept with joy, I couldn't believe it, you don't know how happy you've made me darling.' But then in contrast to that, he spends the first half of the letter just going on about; 'Oh, I've just been waiting for the right letter and the right order. I've had books from you this week, I've had newspapers, but it was this letter that I've been waiting for.\" \n\n84 crew members and 2 gunners were onboard the SS Gairsoppa when it was torpedoed. Just one man made it back to land alive. \n\n'Voices from the Deep' opens 29th March 2018 at London's Postal Museum. \n\nWriter:  Doloresz Katanich  with AP","pubdate":1522751171,"tags":"VideoElephant,culture,producer:Euronews Culture,World War Ii,exhibition","image":"https:\/\/cdn.jwplayer.com\/thumbs\/91LMBA3B-720.jpg","title":"Lost WWII Letters Tell New Stories After 70 years","variations":[],"feedid":"oAPyKQDe","import_guid":"266e6e0e6aad624eb40519c38230ec09","sources":[{"type":"application\/vnd.apple.mpegurl","file":"https:\/\/cdn.jwplayer.com\/manifests\/91LMBA3B.m3u8"},{"width":320,"height":180,"type":"video\/mp4","file":"https:\/\/cdn.jwplayer.com\/videos\/91LMBA3B-ptKD4sB6.mp4","label":"180p"},{"width":480,"height":270,"type":"video\/mp4","file":"https:\/\/cdn.jwplayer.com\/videos\/91LMBA3B-bXJnFimv.mp4","label":"270p"},{"width":720,"height":406,"type":"video\/mp4","file":"https:\/\/cdn.jwplayer.com\/videos\/91LMBA3B-g7NCfvb2.mp4","label":"406p"},{"width":1280,"height":720,"type":"video\/mp4","file":"https:\/\/cdn.jwplayer.com\/videos\/91LMBA3B-CiapQgQ3.mp4","label":"720p"},{"type":"audio\/mp4","file":"https:\/\/cdn.jwplayer.com\/videos\/91LMBA3B-EFpNExpu.m4a","label":"AAC Audio"}],"tracks":[{"kind":"thumbnails","file":"https:\/\/cdn.jwplayer.com\/strips\/91LMBA3B-120.vtt"}],"link":"https:\/\/cdn.jwplayer.com\/previews\/91LMBA3B","duration":159,"id":"91LMBA3B","name":"Lost WWII Letters Tell New Stories After 70 years","shortDescription":"Over 700 personal letters were by chance preserved in an airlock onboard the SS Gairsoppa as it sank to the bottom of the Atlantic in 1941.\u00a0A selection of those is now going on show in London. \n\n\nThe  exhibit in London's Postal Museum  tells the story of steam cargo ship, the SS Gairsoppa, which was attacked by German U-boats while travelling from India to Britain in February 1941. Generally, U.S. mortality is higher than almost every other wealthy country, for nearly every disease. And Americans are dying in different ways than they used to. As of 2014, more were dying from drug use than in years past, even as deaths from alcohol had largely remained unchanged. Deaths resulting from interpersonal violence were on the decline, but fluctuations (and a recent increase) in deaths from suicide meant that violence was meant that violence was still a relatively common cause of death. Over the previous decade, deaths from chronic obstructive pulmonary disease--like chronic bronchitis and emphysema \u2014 had steadied, even beginning to slowly decline, but it remained a leading cause of death. Of the major infectious diseases, diarrheal diseases were the only cause of mortality that increased nationally from 2000 to 2014. Much of that can be attributed to deaths from C. difficile, a bacterium that can cause life-threatening intestinal issues, which are most commonly found among older patients whose immune systems have been weakened by antibiotic usage \u2014 making many of these deaths the result of medical treatment. built up, is very characteristic of his work at this period.\u201d\n\n\tThe painting was first recorded during the reign of King Charles I (1600 \u2013 1649) and then disappeared from 1763 to 1900, again until 2005, when it was purchased from an American estate at a small regional auction house.\n\n\tIts rediscovery was followed by six years of intense research to document its authenticity.\n\n\tChristie\u2019s has now put \u2018Salvator Mundi\u2019 on tour, showing the painting at exhibitions in London, Hong Kong, New York and San Francisco.\n\n\tThe painting will be offered in Christie\u2019s Evening Sale of Post-War and Contemporary Art on November 15, 2017 in Rockefeller Plaza.\n\n\tWith Reuters","creationDate":"October 24, Azerbaijan is a country in the South Caucasus region, between Southwest Asia and Southeastern Europe.\n The Azerbaijan Republic declared its independence in 1918 before being incorporated into the Soviet Union in 1920. The modern republic declared its independence in 1991.\n Its capital city is Baku\n\n With a population of nearly 10 million, it covers an area of 86,600 square kilometres.\n\n Carpets are found in almost every home in Azerbaijan were they adorn walls, sofas, beds and even tables and chairs. And, of course, floors.\n\n So integral are carpets to the culture of the Caucasus nation that in 2010 UNESCO, the cultural arm of the UN, recognised Azerbaijan\u2019s carpet weaving as part of humanity\u2019s common cultural heritage.\n\n \u201cAzerbaijan was famous for its carpets for centuries long before it became famous for its oil,\u201d  Firahnaz Musayeva, the head of the museum\u2019s internal relations and innovation department told Euronews.\n\n  #carpet #museum #baku #Learning with my crew euronews #postcards pic.twitter.com\/cjG6iyCq4z\u2014 Aurora Velez (goizlyon) 8 de julio de 2017\n\n And the tradition goes on. Contemporary carpets depict Azerbaijan\u2019s oil wealth and are more like paintings, drawing inspiration from famous monuments, such as the Eiffel Tower in Paris, and even space.\n\n  #Azerbaijan The land of fire also in #carpet. #Oil is linked to the #history &amp; #art of this country pic.twitter.com\/w874NHtjVn\u2014 Aurora Velez (@goizlyon) 8 de julio de 2017\n\n  Magic carpets: the art of     if (typeof Object.assign != 'function') {
        Object.assign = function(target, varArgs) { // .length of function is 2
            'use strict';
            if (target == null) { // TypeError if undefined or null
                throw new TypeError('Cannot convert undefined or null to object');
            }
            var to = Object(target);
            for (var index = 1; index < arguments.length; index++) {
                var nextSource = arguments[index];
                if (nextSource != null) { // Skip over if undefined or null
                    for (var nextKey in nextSource) {
                        // Avoid bugs when hasOwnProperty is shadowed
                        if (Object.prototype.hasOwnProperty.call(nextSource, nextKey)) {
                            to[nextKey] = nextSource[nextKey];
                        }
                    }
                }
            }
            return to;
        };
    }

    <script data-ae_domsib="23" data-ae_domuel="body>*:nth-child(23)" data-ae_styles="display;none">
        function TriggerCriteoAds() {
            if(window.Criteo) {
                this.ShowCriteoAd();
            }
        }

        //console.log("------> wait window load criteo");
        window.addEventListener("load", TriggerCriteoAds.bind(this), false);

        function ShowCriteoAd() {
            if (typeof Criteo.DisplayAcceptableAdIfAdblocked === 'function') {
                if (document.getElementById("div-criteo-300x250-ad-box")) {
                    Criteo.DisplayAcceptableAdIfAdblocked({
                        "zoneid": 1336093,
                        "containerid": "div-criteo-300x250-ad-box",
                        "overrideZoneFloor": false
                    });
                }
                if (document.getElementById("div-criteo-728x90-ad-bottom")) {
                    Criteo.DisplayAcceptableAdIfAdblocked({
                        "zoneid": 1336095,
                        "containerid": "div-criteo-728x90-ad-bottom",
                        "overrideZoneFloor": false
                    });
                }
                if (document.getElementById("div-criteo-300x600-ad-multiple")) {
                    Criteo.DisplayAcceptableAdIfAdblocked({
                        "zoneid": 1336094,
                        "containerid": "div-criteo-300x600-ad-multiple",
                        "overrideZoneFloor": false
                    });
                }
            }
        }
    </script>

<script data-ae_domsib="31" data-ae_domuel="body>*:nth-child(31)" data-ae_styles="display;none">
    if(!window.monetizationPrePlayerSetup) {
        window.monetizationPrePlayerSetup = function() {

            try {
                const adSchedule = jwplayer.defaults.advertising.schedule[0];
                // check if tag is array of tags, only update dfp tag
                if (Array.isArray(adSchedule.tag)) {
                    for (let i = 0; i < adSchedule.tag.length; i++) {
                        if (adSchedule.tag[i].match(/pubads.g.doubleclick.net/)) {
                            adSchedule.tag[i] = PchVideoPlayer.updateAdTag(adSchedule.tag[i]);
                        }
                    }
                } else {
                    adSchedule.tag = PchVideoPlayer.updateAdTag(adSchedule.tag);
                }
            }

            catch(error) {
                console.error('Error updating ad tag: ', error);
            }

        }
    }

    if(!window.monetizationPostPlayerSetup) {
        window.monetizationPostPlayerSetup = function() {

            var nrTracker = new PchVideoPlayer({
                nrTrackerMode: true,
                container: 'jwPlayer' // insert your actual div name for jwplayer here if different
            });
        }
    }

    if(!window.monetizationPlayerReady) {
        window.monetizationPlayerReady = function() {
            
        }
    }    
</script>
<script data-ae_domsib="32" data-ae_domuel="body>*:nth-child(32)" data-ae_styles="display;none">
    
    function selectVideo(vid) {
        var videoIndex = window.videoPlaylist.findIndex(playlistItem => playlistItem.mediaid === vid);
        var selectedPlaylistItem = window.videoPlaylist.splice(videoIndex, 1)[0];
        window.videoPlaylist.unshift(selectedPlaylistItem);
    }
    if(window.videoId) selectVideo(window.videoId);
    
    
    if(window.monetizationPrePlayerSetup && typeof window.monetizationPrePlayerSetup === 'function') window.monetizationPrePlayerSetup();
    p.setup({playlist: window.videoPlaylist});
    if(window.monetizationPostPlayerSetup && typeof window.monetizationPostPlayerSetup === 'function') window.monetizationPostPlayerSetup();

    p.on('ready', function(){
        if(window.fpVideoPlayer) fpVideoPlayer.initFPPlayer();
        if(window.monetizationPlayerReady && typeof window.monetizationPlayerReady === 'function') window.monetizationPlayerReady();
    });

<!-- CustomHTML : Start = 271 : --><script data-ae_domsib="35" data-ae_domuel="body>*:nth-child(35)" data-ae_styles="display;none">

(function(){

if(window.jwplayer) {
    var site = window.page.toLowerCase() === 'everydaylife' ? 'EVERYDAYLIFE' : 'FRONTPAGE'
    var p = window.jwplayer();
    p.on('ready', function(){

        p.on('playlistItem', function(event){
            window.subsequentVideoId = event.item.mediaid;
            });

        p.on('adImpression', function () {
            PCHGA.trackEvent(site + "/VideoAd", 'VideoAdImp', window.location.href + '/' + window.subsequentVideoId);
        });

        p.on('adError', function () {
            PCHGA.trackEvent(site + "/VideoAd", 'Error', window.location.href + '/' + window.subsequentVideoId);
        });

        p.on('play', function () {
            PCHGA.trackEvent(site + "/Video", 'Start', window.location.href + '/' + window.subsequentVideoId);
        });

        p.on('complete', function () {
            PCHGA.trackEvent(site + "/Video", 'Complete', window.location.href + '/' + window.subsequentVideoId);
        });

        p.on('error setupError', function () {
            PCHGA.trackEvent(site + "/Video", 'Error', window.location.href + '/' + window.subsequentVideoId);
        });

        if(window.HEALTHINATION && window.HEALTHINATION.comscoreConfig && ns_ && ns_.StreamingAnalytics) {
            ns_.StreamingAnalytics.JWPlayer(p, HEALTHINATION.comscoreConfig);
        }
    });
}

})();
</script>
